Relationships and Cardinalities

The following relationships define how different entities in the e-commerce system interact with each other:

  1. Customers → Orders

Relationship: A customer places orders
Cardinality: One-to-Many (1:N)
Explanation: A single customer can place multiple orders, but each order belongs to only one customer.

---

  2. Customers → Addresses

Relationship: A customer has addresses
Cardinality: One-to-Many (1:N)
Explanation: A customer can have multiple addresses (e.g., home, office), but each address is associated with only one customer.

---

  3. Orders → Payments

Relationship: An order has a payment
Cardinality: One-to-One (1:1)
Explanation: Each order is linked to one payment record, and each payment corresponds to one specific order.

---

  4. Orders → Order_Items

Relationship: An order contains items
Cardinality: One-to-Many (1:N)
Explanation: A single order can contain multiple items, but each order item belongs to only one order.

---

  5. Products → Order_Items

Relationship: A product appears in order items
Cardinality: One-to-Many (1:N)
Explanation: A product can be included in multiple order items, but each order item refers to one specific product.

---

  6. Orders ↔ Products (via Order_Items)

Relationship: Many-to-Many (M:N)
Resolved By: Order_Items table
Explanation:

 One order can contain multiple products
 One product can appear in multiple orders
 This many-to-many relationship is resolved using the Order_Items table

---

  7. Categories → Products

Relationship: A category contains products
Cardinality: One-to-Many (1:N)
Explanation: A category can include multiple products, but each product belongs to only one category.

Relationship Summary Table
Relationship	Type	Cardinality	Description
Customers → Addresses	One-to-Many	1	A customer can have multiple addresses
Customers → Orders	One-to-Many	1	A customer can place multiple orders
Orders → Order_Items	One-to-Many	1	An order contains multiple products
Products → Order_Items	One-to-Many	1	A product can be part of many orders
Categories → Products	One-to-Many	1	A category contains multiple products
Products → Inventory	One-to-One	1:1	Each product has one inventory record
Orders → Payments	One-to-One	1:1	Each order has one payment

Explanation

One-to-Many (1): One record in a table is related to multiple records in another table.

One-to-One (1:1): One record in a table is linked to exactly one record in another table.

Many-to-Many (M): Resolved using a junction table (Order_Items in this case).
